   {:e #blake3 "8983f4d6d36b8cf4f183093b49ed89f83c6d1b0f6b60a231bf1049f1a591548c" :a :db/ident :v :harvest/session-braid-user-1774106861 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "8983f4d6d36b8cf4f183093b49ed89f83c6d1b0f6b60a231bf1049f1a591548c" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :recon/trace-4aaa9577bb2ef1b7; LIFECYCLE-VERIFICATION-LAYER: The temporal coherence gap — bilateral loop checks spatial coherence (spec↔impl at a point in time) but not temporal coherence (do lifecycle properties hold over time). Five temporal properties currently unverified: (1) sessions eventually close, (2) observations eventually crystallize, (3) specs eventually get implemented, (4) implementations eventually get tested, (5) F(S) never decreases under normal operation. Proposed L(t) metric: lifecycle coherence = fulfilled expectations / total expectations. Implementation via lifecycle expectations stored as datoms (:expect/event, :expect/trigger-tx, :expect/deadline, :expect/status). After each transact(), check overdue expectations, register new ones. Δ-lifecycle is the fourth metabolic component. But the FIRST-PRINCIPLES insight: lifecycle invariants should be ENFORCED at transition points, not MONITORED after the fact. Cotransaction IS enforcement. L(t) monitoring is SECONDARY verification that enforcement is working. TRACES TO: INV-BILATERAL-001, INV-HARVEST-007, INV-STORE-014.; Session entity: :recon/trace-e5a6d434187bf142; UNIVERSAL-OBSERVE-VISION: The ultimate endpoint of the cotransaction principle. braid observe becomes the single universal intake — the agent says what they know, the system routes it to the correct pipeline layers automatically. Five cotransaction rules: Rule 1 (spec-ref → spec annotation): observation referencing existing INV/ADR/NEG creates spec annotation + flags witness staleness. Rule 2 (falsification language → auto-crystallize): observation with falsification patterns + spec namespace + confidence >= 0.8 creates :spec/finding entity. Rule 3 (actionable language → auto-task): observation with action patterns + file/component refs creates task with --force. Rule 4 (decision language → ADR skeleton): observation with decision patterns + rationale creates ADR skeleton. Rule 5 (question language → open question): observation with question patterns + confidence < 0.7 creates open question entity. All rules fire in the SAME transaction as the observation — cotransacted, not sequential. The agent doesn't need to know DDIS ontology. They just say what they know. Basin A wins by making methodology invisible. DEPENDS-ON: harvest-session cotransaction (foundation). TRACES TO: INV-GUIDANCE-014, INV-GUIDANCE-024, INV-HARVEST-007, ADR-GUIDANCE-002.; Session entity: :recon/trace-a757e4b0b0d2193a; Session entity: :recon/trace-e65db5dd69e23f13; PERFORMANCE: braid status takes 36 seconds with release binary at 33k datoms. Root cause needs investigation — likely boundary evaluation (default_boundaries().evaluate_all) or R(t) routing (compute_action_from_store). A --fast flag that skips bilateral, boundaries, methodology gaps, and R(t) routing would provide sub-1s dashboard. Shows only: store size, F(S) (cached), P(t), harvest urgency, session delta. TRACES TO: INV-INTERFACE-008, ADR-STORE-005.; Session entity: :recon/trace-67fb8b9b9255aaab; STALE-SESSION-BUG-ANALYSIS: Session s-1773271079 from Session 021 was never closed, blocking auto-session-detection for 10+ sessions. Root cause: harvest does not close the active session — it writes harvest metadata but leaves session status unchanged. detect_session_start sees the old active session and returns false (session exists, skip). The fix was two-part: (1) manual transact to close the stale session, (2) add 2-hour staleness threshold to detect_session_start. But the deeper issue: the test suite verified the FUNCTION (detect_session_start works on a fresh store) but not the LIFECYCLE (session creates → work → harvest → session closes → next command → new session). Unit tests cover point-in-time state properties. Lifecycle properties (liveness: 'sessions eventually close') require temporal verification across multiple operations. This is the safety vs liveness gap: F(S) measures safety (nothing bad at this moment) but not liveness (something good eventually happens). TRACES TO: INV-HARVEST-007, INV-BILATERAL-001, INV-STORE-014.; Session entity: :recon/trace-96ae549d78e7dd9e; Session entity: :recon/trace-f66778052799c920; Session entity: :recon/trace-45ef4bbca7775261; Session entity: :recon/trace-7fbd0516b4bafd2c; Session entity: :task/t-7412b5f4; Session entity: :recon/trace-df3b33c50df2d51d; Session entity: :recon/trace-450c8c60229cbc6e; Session entity: :recon/trace-f5bacaa481e4c4a4; HARVEST-SESSION-COTRANSACTION: The highest-priority cotransaction. Harvest becomes the session boundary — old session closes and new session opens in the SAME transaction. Implementation: in harvest::run() after building all_datoms: (1) query active session entity. (2) append session-close datoms (status→closed). (3) generate new session entity with start-fitness, start-datom-count, started-at, status=active. (4) append new session datoms. (5) existing write_tx commits everything atomically. ~30 lines. The detect_session_start in main.rs remains as cold-start fallback. Benefits: session progress dashboard (META-7) becomes exact (session boundary = harvest boundary). Metabolic deltas segment cleanly into sessions. Stale session class of bug becomes impossible by construction. Every future cotransaction's datoms land in correctly-bounded sessions. This is the CAUSAL PREREQUISITE for all other cotransactions — incorrect session boundaries corrupt all downstream metrics. TRACES TO: INV-HARVEST-007, INV-BILATERAL-001, INV-STORE-014.; Session entity: :recon/trace-4170eefc83984ab3; Session entity: :recon/trace-ec5ff3af99e5c5a2; BUG: Session s-1773271079 from Session 021 was never closed. detect_session_start sees it as active and skips auto-creation. All subsequent sessions inherit this stale session entity. Fix: either close the stale session and let auto-detect create a new one, or enhance detect_session_start to check session AGE (a session from days ago is not 'active' in any meaningful sense). Root cause: session end (harvest) doesn't auto-close the active session. The braid session end command exists but is never called automatically. TRACES TO: INV-HARVEST-007, INV-BILATERAL-001.; Session entity: :recon/trace-d44e47f5473915d6; Session entity: :recon/trace-4d81818da9f514e8; Session entity: :recon/trace-dbf8bb7767c21df6; COTRANSACTION-PRINCIPLE: Phase transitions in an append-only knowledge system must be atomic or they will eventually fail. The session bug is an instance of a general pattern: when event A necessarily implies event B (harvest implies session-close), they must share a transaction. Not 'A triggers B' (causal, sequential, gap-prone). Not 'A and B are checked for consistency' (monitoring, after-the-fact). A and B are COTRANSACTED — datoms in the same transaction, committed atomically. Five cotransaction boundaries identified: (1) Harvest→Session rotation (harvest closes old session + opens new one atomically). (2) Observe→Crystallize (structured observations auto-crystallize spec elements in same tx). (3) Spec→Task (new spec elements auto-generate implementation tasks in same tx). (4) Trace→Witness (new code→spec links auto-generate FBW witness skeletons in same tx). (5) Close→Verify (task closure includes CBV evidence in same tx — partially implemented). The principle derives from CRDT theory: in an append-only system with no global clock, the only mechanism preserving boundary integrity is CO-LOCATION in the same transaction. TRACES TO: INV-STORE-001, INV-HARVEST-007, INV-TASK-006, INV-WITNESS-001.; Session entity: :recon/trace-1d2274f279e66b8b; Session entity: :session/s-1774104771; Session entity: :recon/trace-b150683e97e63fa5; Session entity: :recon/trace-60e03b25080e9646; Session entity: :recon/trace-8180c5638cd797ee; Session entity: :recon/trace-9ddbf7e7dc5af82f; PERF-STATUS-36S: braid status takes 36 seconds with release binary at 33k datoms. Needs --fast flag that skips bilateral, boundaries, methodology gaps, R(t) routing. Shows only: store size, F(S) cached, P(t), harvest urgency, session delta. Target: sub-1 second. Task created as t-7412b5f4 (PERF-1). TRACES TO: INV-INTERFACE-008.; Session entity: :recon/trace-44dcee230be972b2; Session entity: :recon/trace-2acfa71611d3d9be\nSession entity: :task/t-f5b1a51f; Session entity: :task/t-65c81ecd; Session entity: :task/t-afd66aca; Session entity: :task/t-222d6fdc; Session entity: :task/t-c9eb2524; Session entity: :task/t-d70a1d49; Session entity: :task/t-b1ab00b6" :op :assert}
